      "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
      "body": "If this `nTime` was used merely for computing the difficulty, it can stay `uint32_t` and the only thing requiring change would be something like adding a condition `if block_time_2016_back > block_time_now { do_simple_magic; }` which would normalize (offset) both of the two values (the overflown lower and before-overflow bigger, rendering them like they are supposed to be) and carry on with the difficulty computation like normal. Yes, it would require some minimum Bitcoin Core version, but the sooner it gets implemented, the sooner are compatible nodes running. The fix can be also easily back-ported to older stable branches.\r\n\r\nIs my thinking right that the the related value of `uint32_t` type stored in each block can be (or already is?) used merely in difficulty computation so that everything can stay as it is and no hard-fork is needed?",
